hints_latex:
Recall that the integral

\begin{align*}
\int_a^b f(x)\,dx
\end{align*}

is given by

\begin{align*}
\lim_{N \to \infty} \sum_{i=1}^N f\left(a+i\triangle x\right)\triangle x
\end{align*}

where

\begin{align*}
\triangle x = \frac{b-a}{N}
\end{align*}

Following from the first hint:

\begin{align*}
\int_a^b f(x)\,dx = \lim_{N \to \infty} \sum_{i=1}^N f(a+i(b-a)/N) \frac{b-a}{N}
\end{align*}

and in this case, we have \emph{a} = -1 and \emph{b} = 2 for $f(x)=x-1$.

sols_latex:
Since $f(a+i(b-a)/N) = f(-1+3i/N) = -1+3i/N - 1$ we follow the hints, to
obtain

\begin{align*}
\int_{-1}^2 (x-1) \,dx &= \lim_{N \to \infty} \sum_{i=1}^N f(-1+3i/N)\frac{3}{N}\\
&= \lim_{N \to \infty} \sum_{i=1}^N (-1+3i/N - 1)\frac{3}{N}\\
&= \lim_{N \to \infty} \frac{3}{N} \sum_{i=1}^N \left(-2+ \frac{3i}{N}\right)\\
&= \lim_{N \to \infty} \left( -\frac{6}{N} \sum_{i=1}^N 1 + \frac{9}{N^2} \sum_{i=1}^N i \right)
\end{align*}

Since

\begin{align*}
\sum_{i=1}^N i = N \quad \text{ and }\quad \sum_{i=1}^N i = \frac{N(N+1)}{2},
\end{align*}

we can continue our computation

\begin{align*}
\int_{-1}^2 (x-1) \,dx &= \lim_{N \to \infty} \left( -\frac{6}{N}N + \frac{9}{N^2} \frac{N(N+1)}{2} \right)\\
&= -6 + \frac{9}{2}\lim_{N \to \infty}\frac{N+1}{N}\\
&= -6 + \frac{9}{2}\\
&= -\frac{3}{2}.
\end{align*}

\emph{You can always compare your answer to the computation of the
integral directly and see that the answers match:}

\begin{align*}
\int_{-1}^2 (x-1)\,dx &= \left.\frac{x^2}2-x\right|_{-1}^2 \\
&= \frac42 - 2 - \left(\frac12 + 1\right) \\
&= -\frac32.
\end{align*}

